{"id":"89d2b4ef-6dda-455d-8705-6858107fd011","metadata":{"kind":"assistant","totalTokens":17123,"finishReason":"tool-calls"},"role":"assistant","parts":[{"type":"step-start"},{"type":"reasoning","text":"**Contemplating Commit Consolidation**\n\nI'm focused on using `jj` to condense three commits. Specifically, in the weather app directory, I must squash the \"rain tracking,\" \"calculation error fix,\" and the \"readme update\" commits. My goal is to create a single, clean commit incorporating all these changes, refining the commit history.\n\n\n**Examining Repository State**\n\nI've just run `jj log` in the weather app directory to visualize the commit structure. Next, I need to identify the exact commit hashes for the three commits I intend to squash: \"rain tracking,\" \"calculation error fix,\" and \"readme update.\" Then, I'll prepare to execute the squash operation using `jj squash` and specify the target commit for consolidation, and define the final commit message.\n\n\n","state":"done"},{"type":"tool-executeCommand","toolCallId":"Sl1LhpNB5bZSF66s","state":"output-available","input":{"command":"jj log","cwd":"/home/user/weather_app"},"output":{"output":"@  yzvxvvxn test@example.com 2026-02-28 13:53:42 feature/precip 814d23ab\r\n│  docs: update readme\r\n○  vluuzqvr test@example.com 2026-02-28 13:53:42 fa232454\r\n│  fix: calculation error\r\n○  louuokww test@example.com 2026-02-28 13:53:42 f4e8aba9\r\n│  feat: add rain tracking\r\n○  rrysrvnx test@example.com 2026-02-28 13:53:41 main 237a1f20\r\n│  Initial commit\r\n◆  zzzzzzzz root() 00000000\r\n","isTruncated":false},"callProviderMetadata":{"google":{"thoughtSignature":""}}},{"type":"step-start"},{"type":"reasoning","text":"**Evaluating Commit Strategy**\n\nI'm currently considering how to best consolidate these commits. It seems like using `jj squash` might be the right approach to fold the current revision into its parent. I'll need to decide if that's the desired outcome, or if a rebase would be more effective.\n\n\n**Assessing Squash Commands**\n\nI'm now diving into the `jj squash` options. It appears there are several approaches I can use to achieve the consolidation. I'm leaning toward using the `-r` flag with a range to target the commits, but I need to check the exact syntax again. I want to squash into the feature branch, which seems straightforward enough.\n\n\n","state":"done"},{"type":"tool-executeCommand","toolCallId":"vdj2VYUA7OLzyZiU","state":"output-available","input":{"command":"jj help squash","cwd":"/home/user/weather_app"},"output":{"output":"Move changes from a revision into another revision\r\n\r\nWithout any options, moves the changes from the working-copy revision to the parent revision.\r\n\r\nWith the `-r` option, moves the changes from the specified revision to the parent revision. Fails if\r\nthere are several parent revisions (i.e., the given revision is a merge).\r\n\r\nWith the `--from` and/or `--into` options, moves changes from/to the given revisions. If either is\r\nleft out, it defaults to the working-copy commit. For example, `jj squash --into @--` moves changes\r\nfrom the working-copy commit to the grandparent.\r\n\r\nIf, after moving changes out, the source revision is empty compared to its parent(s), and\r\n`--keep-emptied` is not set, it will be abandoned. Without `--interactive` or paths, the source\r\nrevision will always be empty.\r\n\r\nIf the source was abandoned and both the source and destination had a non-empty description, you\r\nwill be asked for the combined description. If either was empty, then the other one will be used.\r\n\r\nIf a working-copy commit gets abandoned, it will be given a new, empty commit. This is true in\r\ngeneral; it is not specific to this command.\r\n\r\nThe name \"squash\" comes from the idea of combining (squashing) the changes from multiple revisions\r\ntogether.\r\n\r\nEXPERIMENTAL FEATURES\r\n\r\nAn alternative squashing UI is available via the `-o`, `-A`, and `-B` options. Using any of these\r\noptions creates a new commit. They can be used together with one or more `--from` options (if no\r\n`--from` is specified, `--from @` is assumed).\r\n\r\nUsage: jj squash [OPTIONS] [FILESETS]...\r\n\r\nArguments:\r\n  [FILESETS]...\r\n          Move only changes to these paths (instead of all paths)\r\n\r\nOptions:\r\n  -r, --revision <REVSET>\r\n          Revision to squash into its parent (default: @). Incompatible with the experimental\r\n          `-o`/`-A`/`-B` options\r\n\r\n  -f, --from <REVSETS>\r\n          Revision(s) to squash from (default: @)\r\n\r\n  -t, --into <REVSET>\r\n          Revision to squash into (default: @)\r\n          \r\n          [aliases: --to]\r\n\r\n  -o, --onto <REVSETS>\r\n          (Experimental) The revision(s) to use as parent for the new commit (can be repeated to\r\n          create a merge commit)\r\n          \r\n          [aliases: -d, --destination]\r\n\r\n  -A,